<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 8:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I27da1d50630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>8.</label.designator><headtext>Relevancy</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71ff016682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>8:16.</label.designator><headtext>Ballistics and gunpowder residue tests</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Georgia admitted ballistic evidence as early as 1876 when an expert testified about the length of time since a gun had been fired and the kind of shot found in a wound.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7946403074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Since then, ballistic evidence has been freely admitted.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7946403174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference><?page no="251"?>] The expert witness should state that in his opinion the test bullet and the bullet in question were fired from the same gun and should not state that this is an “established fact.”[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7946403274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The court allowed a non-expert witness to testify as to calibre.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7946674074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">4</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="2003632788" w-seq-number="00012" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief19a19274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Jones v. State</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7946674174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">5</footnote.reference>] the Georgia Supreme Court held in a felony murder prosecution that an atomic absorption test, which tests for gunshot residue, was scientifically reliable under the test established in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1982125527" w-seq-number="00014" w-ref-type="RT" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief1a64e274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5"><ital>Harper</ital></cite.query>,[<footnote.reference refid="I7946674274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">6</footnote.reference>] and the results were admissible. <eos/><bos/>Issues involving technological advances that have purportedly made barium and antimony more common in the environment, the failure to test the gun itself, and the lack of blind testing went to the weight of the evidence rather than to its admissibility.[<eos/><bos/><footnote.reference refid="I7946674374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">7</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I7946403074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1876005538" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" ID="Ief155bd174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Moughon v. State, 57 Ga. 102, 1876 WL 3098 (1876)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946403174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1934106828" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Ief15d10274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Gibson v. State, 178 Ga. 707, 174 S.E. 354 (1934)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1943105031" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief15d10574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Lewis v. State, 196 Ga. 755, 27 S.E.2d 659 (1943)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1951105108" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief15d10874d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Henderson v. State, 208 Ga. 73, 65 S.E.2d 175 (1951)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1950117261" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000107" ID="Ief15d10b74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Goodall v. U.S., 180 F.2d 397, 17 A.L.R.2d 1070 (D.C. Cir. 1950)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1959124469" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000107" ID="Ief15d10f74d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Atwood, 250 N.C. 141, 108 S.E.2d 219, 86 A.L.R.2d 602 (1959)</cite.query>; <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="2038422868" w-seq-number="00007" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief15d11274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Ford v. State, 298 Ga. 560, 783 S.E.2d 906 (2016)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1979106126" w-seq-number="00008" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief166d4274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Sims v. State, 243 Ga. 83, 252 S.E.2d 501 (1979)</cite.query><?page no="251"?>, the ballistic evidence was properly admitted and the bullet was sufficiently identified.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The Georgia Supreme Court, in <cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="2004502166" w-seq-number="00009" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief17098274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Al Amin v. State, 278 Ga. 74, 597 S.E.2d 332 (2004)</cite.query>, held that the trial court did not err in refusing to conduct a Harper hearing regarding the admissibility of firearms/ballistic/tool marks evidence because such ballistics evidence <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“is not novel, and has been widely accepted in Georgia courts.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946403274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1939106641" w-seq-number="00010" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief1757a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Bruno v. State, 189 Ga. 74, 5 S.E.2d 376 (1939)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946674074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>4</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1909013034" w-seq-number="00011" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000710" ID="Ief19055274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Garner v. State, 6 Ga. App. 788, 65 S.E. 842 (1909)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946674174d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>5</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="2003632788" w-seq-number="00013" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief19c8a274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jones v. State, 277 Ga. 36, 586 S.E.2d 224 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946674274d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>6</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="1982125527" w-seq-number="00015" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief1a8bf274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Harper v. State, 249 Ga. 519, 292 S.E.2d 389 (1982)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I7946674374d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>7</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287017141" w-serial-number="2003632788" w-seq-number="00016" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="Ief1ada1274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Jones v. State, 277 Ga. 36, 586 S.E.2d 224 (2003)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 8:16<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
